<DetailPostLayout
  title="Agora"
  description="A comprehensive UX research and design project creating a peer support platform for university students, addressing help-seeking challenges through evidence-based design solutions."
  keywords="UX research,user experience design,peer learning platform,university students,qualitative research,semi-structured interviews,accessibility design,responsive design"
>
  <div class="post">
    <main class="post-wrapper">
      <DetailHeader
        tag="UX RESEARCH & DESIGN"
        description="Oct - Dec 2020 â€¢ Academic Project">
        <h1 class="font-type">
          Agora
        </h1>
      </DetailHeader>

      <section class="agora-content">
        <div class="hero-container">
          <div class="hero-image-wrapper">
            <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/63d2895db64bcc13414173ec_0.0-login%20(1).png" alt="Agora platform login interface showing clean, accessible design with university credential integration" class="hero-image" />
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="project-details-section">
          <div class="detail-card">
            <h4>My Role</h4>
            <p>Lead UX Researcher & Product Designer</p>
            <p class="detail-sub">Research planning, interview moderation, thematic analysis, interaction design, accessibility audit</p>
          </div>
          <div class="detail-card">
            <h4>Team & Timeline</h4>
            <p>Moshi Qin, Annika Halonen, Mariana Perez</p>
            <p class="detail-sub">8 weeks</p>
          </div>
          <div class="detail-card">
            <h4>Methods & Tools</h4>
            <p>Semi-structured interviews, thematic analysis, wireframing, high-fidelity prototyping</p>
            <p class="detail-sub">Figma, Zoom, content analysis, accessibility testing</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="overview-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">01</span>
            <h2>Problem Context & Research Foundation</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="section-content">
            <p>
              University help-seeking is fragmented and inefficient. Students rely on personal networks through messaging apps (WhatsApp, Telegram, Teams, Discord), but newcomers and international students lack these connections. Our preliminary research revealed two critical gaps: <strong>students struggle to identify the "right person"</strong> to ask, and <strong>response time uncertainty</strong> creates decision-making anxiety.
            </p>
            <div class="problem-stats">
              <div class="stat-item">
                <span class="stat-number">5/6</span>
                <span class="stat-label">students prefer asking peers over teachers for initial help</span>
              </div>
              <div class="stat-item">
                <span class="stat-number">3/6</span>
                <span class="stat-label">report difficulty "finding the right person" to answer questions</span>
              </div>
              <div class="stat-item">
                <span class="stat-number">4/6</span>
                <span class="stat-label">experience anxiety about email response wait times</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p>
              <strong>Our hypothesis:</strong> A platform that combines public forum reach, private thread psychological safety, and direct 1:1 messagingâ€”with clear credibility and availability signalsâ€”could bridge these gaps and create sustainable peer learning networks.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="research-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">02</span>
            <h2>Research Methodology & Process</h2>
          </div>
          
          <div class="research-goals">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading subsection-block">Research Objectives</h3>
            <div class="goals-list">
              <div class="goal-item">
                <span class="goal-number">RQ1</span>
                <p>Understand the dynamics between help-seekers and help-providers (proactive vs. reactive support patterns).</p>
              </div>
              <div class="goal-item">
                <span class="goal-number">RQ2</span>
                <p>Map current help-seeking channels and behavioral preferences across different question complexities.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="goal-item">
                <span class="goal-number">RQ3</span>
                <p>Identify barriers, motivations, and trust-building needs in peer academic support scenarios.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="research-method">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading subsection-block">Semi-structured Interview Study</h3>
            <div class="method-details-grid">
              <div class="method-text">
                <p>
                  <strong>Sample:</strong> 6 participants across 3 universities (Tampere, Turku, Oulu) representing diverse academic levels and cultural backgrounds. Average age 25, gender split 4F/2M, nationalities: Finland (4), Vietnam (1), France (1).
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Protocol:</strong> 45â€“60-minute remote interviews via Zoom with audio recording consent. Each researcher conducted 2 interviews independently to ensure data trustworthiness and avoid acquaintance bias.
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Ethics:</strong> Informed consent obtained, recordings anonymized and deleted post-course completion, participants identified by codes (P1-P6) only.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="participant-breakdown card-style">
                <h4>Participant Demographics</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Education:</strong> 2 BSc, 2 MSc, 2 PhD students</li>
                  <li><strong>Institutions:</strong> 4 Tampere University, 1 Turku University, 1 Oulu University</li>
                  <li><strong>International representation:</strong> 33% non-Finnish participants</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="data-analysis subsection-block">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">Thematic Analysis Process</h3>
            <div class="analysis-container">
              <div class="analysis-text">
                <p>
                  We conducted <strong>content/thematic analysis</strong> using interview questionnaire themes as parent categories. Each researcher analyzed their own interviews, then cross-analyzed others' transcripts for validationâ€”totaling 15 hours of collaborative analysis.
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Key patterns emerged:</strong> 4/6 participants preferred text for simple questions but speaking for complex issues; 2/6 explicitly valued credibility signals; 2/6 desired anonymous asking options; 4/6 were motivated by extrinsic rewards for helping others.
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Reliability measures:</strong> Cross-researcher coding validation, evidence trail from quotes to insights, member checking considerations for future iterations.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="analysis-image">
                 <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/63dba0e40bff1d51f384c924_Group%2080%20(1).png" alt="Thematic analysis process showing affinity mapping and content categorization workflow" />
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="insight-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">03</span>
            <h2>Evidence-Based Insights</h2>
          </div>
          
          <div class="key-insights">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">Primary Research Findings</h3>
            <div class="insights-grid">
              <div class="insight-card">
                <h4>ğŸ¯ Credibility & Discoverability</h4>
                <p><strong>Finding:</strong> 3/6 participants struggled with "finding the right person" to answer questions.</p>
                <p><strong>Evidence:</strong> <em>"Sometimes I do not know who should ask this question like who is the right person that can answer this"</em> (P6, MSc)</p>
                <p><strong>Design implication:</strong> Expert profiles with course/topic tags, ratings, and response time metrics.</p>
              </div>
              
              <div class="insight-card">
                <h4>ğŸ”’ Psychological Safety</h4>
                <p><strong>Finding:</strong> 2/6 participants mentioned anonymity would reduce asking barriers.</p>
                <p><strong>Evidence:</strong> <em>"Maybe in person because I was shy, so asking 75 persons at the same time was a lot for a shy person"</em> (P1, PhD)</p>
                <p><strong>Design implication:</strong> Anonymous-first questioning with optional identity reveal.</p>
              </div>
              
              <div class="insight-card">
                <h4>âš¡ Multi-modal Communication</h4>
                <p><strong>Finding:</strong> Communication method correlates with question complexityâ€”text for simple, voice/video for complex.</p>
                <p><strong>Evidence:</strong> <em>"If it's just a yes, no question... usually I just send an email. But personally, I prefer talk to people face to face... text messages are not enough"</em> (P5, P6)</p>
                <p><strong>Design implication:</strong> Integrated text, audio, and video messaging capabilities.</p>
              </div>
              
              <div class="insight-card">
                <h4>ğŸ”„ Reactive Helping Behavior</h4>
                <p><strong>Finding:</strong> 4/6 participants preferred responding to help requests rather than proactively seeking people to help.</p>
                <p><strong>Evidence:</strong> <em>"If someone asks me, then I'm more than happy to help them... but I don't really actively go around, telling people that I can help them"</em> (P5, PhD)</p>
                <p><strong>Design implication:</strong> Help-seeker centered design with expert matching system.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="design-image-container">
            <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/63dba2682581868b565136c6_Bracket%20Template%20(Community).png" alt="Research insights visualization showing user journey mapping and key pain points" class="full-width-image" />
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="user-groups-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">04</span>
            <h2>User Archetypes & Strategic Focus</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="user-groups-content">
            <p>
              Based on behavioral analysis, we identified two complementary user groups: <strong>Help-Seekers</strong> (primary) and <strong>Experts</strong> (secondary). Our research revealed that helpers typically respond reactively rather than proactively search for people to help.
            </p>
            <div class="highlight-box">
              <p><strong>Strategic Insight:</strong> Focus on optimizing the Help-Seeker experience first to generate demand signals, then use reputation systems and lightweight incentives to attract and retain Experts organically. The "chicken-or-egg" problem suggests Help-Seekers are the activation catalyst.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="user-groups-comparison">
              <div class="user-group card-style">
                <h4>Help-Seekers (Primary Users)</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>New students or course newcomers</li>
                  <li>Value social support over independent search</li>
                  <li>Need fast answers and credible sources</li>
                  <li>Prefer low-barrier asking methods</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="user-group card-style">
                <h4>Experts (Secondary Users)</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Experienced students with topic expertise</li>
                  <li>Motivated by recognition and reciprocity</li>
                  <li>Prefer responding to direct asks vs. searching</li>
                  <li>Value course credits or reputation as incentives</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="design-image-container">
            <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/63dba2f561a25e7b261988b3_Design-37.jpg" alt="User groups analysis showing Help-Seeker and Expert personas with behavioral patterns and motivations" class="full-width-image" />
          	</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="personas-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">05</span>
            <h2>Research-Driven Personas</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="personas-content">
            <p class="personas-intro">
              Our personas synthesize interview data into actionable archetypes. Each persona represents real behavioral patterns, quoted needs, and specific pain points discovered during research, ensuring design decisions remain user-centered throughout development.
            </p>
            <div class="personas-cards">
              <div class="persona-card">
                  <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/63dba3613969af07ac74ebd3_Group%2078.png" alt="Help-seeker persona showing goals, behaviors, and frustrations of new university students seeking academic support" class="persona-image" />
              </div>
              <div class="persona-card">
                  <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/63dba372e8a2c6fa241d240b_Group%2077.png" alt="Expert persona showing motivations and behaviors of experienced students willing to provide peer support" class="persona-image" />
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="goals-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">06</span>
            <h2>Design Goals & Success Criteria</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="goals-content">
            <div class="goals-cards">
              <div class="goals-card">
                <h4>Usability Goals</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Efficiency:</strong> Help-seekers can find suitable expert and request support in â‰¤3 minutes (addressing "waiting time" pain points).</li>
                  <li><strong>Utility:</strong> Support both academic help and student-life guidance with multiple communication modes (text, audio, video).</li>
                  <li><strong>Learnability:</strong> Users understand core workflows without tutorials (critical given initial skepticism toward new platforms).</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="goals-card">
                <h4>User Experience Goals</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Competence:</strong> Users feel capable and confident when asking for or offering help (reduces asking barriers).</li>
                  <li><strong>Safety & Trust:</strong> Low social risk environment with visible credibility signals (expert ratings, response rates).</li>
                  <li><strong>Connection:</strong> Reduce academic isolation and strengthen peer learning communities beyond existing social circles.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="success-metrics">
              <h3 class="subsection-heading">Proposed Success Metrics</h3>
              <div class="metrics-grid">
                <div class="metric-item">
                  <span class="metric-label">Primary:</span>
                  <span class="metric-value">Time to receive help response</span>
                </div>
                <div class="metric-item">
                  <span class="metric-label">Secondary:</span>
                  <span class="metric-value">Expert match satisfaction, Answer quality ratings</span>
                </div>
                <div class="metric-item">
                  <span class="metric-label">Behavioral:</span>
                  <span class="metric-value">Repeat usage, Cross-course help seeking</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="design-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">07</span>
            <h2>Design Process & Rationale</h2>
          </div>
          
          <div class="design-subsection">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">Information Architecture</h3>
            <p>
              The IA organizes around two primary user jobsâ€”<strong>"Ask for help"</strong> and <strong>"Offer help"</strong>â€”with trust & safety woven throughout rather than relegated to secondary flows. This task-centric approach keeps navigation intuitive while supporting both public (reach) and private (safety) interaction modes.
            </p>
            <div class="design-image-container">
              <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/61e2cd0b1ee9e1142e11f34c_sitemap.png" alt="Information architecture sitemap showing Ask Help and Offer Help primary flows with public/private forum options" class="full-width-image" />
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="design-subsection">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">Wireframing & Iteration Process</h3>
            <p>
              Our collaborative design process began with individual wireframing sessions to maintain creative diversity, followed by a structured design workshop using Mural for idea synthesis. Key early decisions included anonymous entry points, expert discovery interfaces, and scheduling integration.
            </p>
            <div class="highlight-box">
              <p><strong>Critical iteration:</strong> Moved text editor toolbar above input field (not inside) to match user mental models and improve usabilityâ€”identified during weekly design reviews.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="design-image-container">
              <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/61e1fdbf9622904f229f01fd_Group%2033%20(1).png" alt="Wireframes" class="full-width-image" />
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="design-subsection">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">Visual Design System</h3>
            <p>
              <strong>Brand attributes:</strong> Reliable, Social, Friendly. We selected warm orange as the primary color to convey approachability and social connection (color psychology research). Poppins + Roboto typography pairing maintains modern readability while feeling welcoming rather than corporate.
            </p>
            <div class="design-principles">
              <div class="principle-item card-style">
                <h4>Color Strategy</h4>
                <p>Orange primary promotes social warmth; accessibility-tested contrast ratios ensure AAA compliance.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="principle-item card-style">
                <h4>Typography Hierarchy</h4>
                <p>Clear H1-H3 heading structure supports screen readers and scanning patterns.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="principle-item card-style">
                <h4>Component System</h4>
                <p>Reusable buttons, cards, and form elements maintain consistency across 15+ screens.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="design-subsection">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">Accessibility Implementation</h3>
            <div class="highlight-box accessibility-details">
              <p><strong>Our accessibility audit ensured inclusive design from day one:</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Color & Contrast:</strong> Body text achieves AAA standard (â‰ˆ7:1 ratio), UI elements meet AA minimum (â‰¥4.5:1). Palette tested for colorblind accessibility using Figma plugins.</li>
                <li><strong>Operability:</strong> Mobile tap targets minimum 60px (42px absolute minimum), clear focus states for keyboard navigation, logical tab order throughout.</li>
                <li><strong>Content Structure:</strong> Meaningful alt text for images, proper heading hierarchy (H1-H3), labeled form controls for screen readers.</li>
                <li><strong>Communication Options:</strong> Text, audio, and video messaging support different accessibility needs and preferences.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="solution-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">08</span>
            <h2>The Solution & Key Features</h2>
          </div>

          <div class="feature-list">
            <div class="feature-item">
              <h4>Anonymous-first Asking</h4>
              <p><strong>Why:</strong> lowers social risk and hesitation to start.</p>
              <p><strong>How:</strong> draft privately with suggested tags; reveal identity later if desired; invite experts into a private thread.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-item">
              <h4>Trust & Availability Signals</h4>
              <p><strong>Why:</strong> students need to judge credibility and responsiveness at a glance.</p>
              <p><strong>How:</strong> course/topic tags, ratings/endorsements, recent activity, response rate, and clear â€œonline/availableâ€ states.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-item">
              <h4>Dual-mode Help</h4>
              <p><strong>Why:</strong> supports both quick unblock and deep mentoring.</p>
              <p><strong>How:</strong> lightweight async Q&A + scheduled 1:1 sessions with integrated availability and booking.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-item">
              <h4>Text + Voice</h4>
              <p><strong>Why:</strong> complex issues are easier to explain verbally for many students.</p>
              <p><strong>How:</strong> voice notes and optional voice calls for private threads and 1:1 messaging.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-item">
              <h4>Reputation & Incentives</h4>
              <p><strong>Why:</strong> sustained expert participation needs recognition and light incentives.</p>
              <p><strong>How:</strong> points/badges, profile highlights, and optional programmatic credit recognition where applicable.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="design-subsection">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">Final Design</h3>
            <p>
              The high-fidelity prototype integrates these decisions into a clean, supportive flow from asking to resolution, emphasizing trust, speed, and safety.
            </p>
            <div class="design-image-container solution-images">
              <img src="https://cdn.prod.website-files.com/61e1afcc293eac3233b2e17f/61e2cc44e4036d68161e20a2_Group%20211%20(1).png" alt="Final solution mockups" class="full-width-image" />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="reflection-section content-section">
          <div class="section-heading">
            <span class="section-number">09</span>
            <h2>Reflection & Next Steps</h2>
          </div>
          <div class="section-content">
            <h3 class="subsection-heading">What I Learned</h3>
            <p>
              Evidence-to-decision mapping kept the team aligned and prevented us from shipping â€œnice-to-haveâ€ features. Prioritizing psychological safety early paid off in clearer flows and stronger adoption intent in feedback.
            </p>

            <h3 class="subsection-heading">Evaluation Plan</h3>
            <div class="evaluation-plan">
              <p>Two rounds of validation will guide iteration:</p>
              <ol>
                <li><strong>Round 1 (qual):</strong> 6 participants (2Ã—BSc/2Ã—MSc/2Ã—PhD) perform core tasks on the hi-fi prototype; capture behavioral notes and post-task ratings.</li>
                <li><strong>Round 2 (task-based):</strong> measure task success, time on task, and SUS/CSAT after iteration; refine trust signals and scheduling affordances.</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </section>
    </main>
  </div>
